		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1463402">People underestimate the risks and consequences of events where they feel in control.<br />
People overestimate the risks and consequences of events where they feel out of control. <br />
<br />
This can be demonstrated in how people perceive risks of driving a car vs flying in an airplane. Or with how people perceive the risks of stuff like ocean acidification, or Iran &quot;getting nukes,&quot; or many of the email hoaxes going around. <br />
<a href="http://www.snopes.com/politics/crime/skyterror.asp" target="_blank">http://www.snopes.com/politics/crime/skyterror.asp</a> <br />
<a href="http://dir.salon.com/story/tech/col/smith/2004/07/21/askthepilot95/index.html" target="_blank">http://dir.salon.com/story/tech/col/...t95/index.html</a> <br />
<br />
More people die in traffic accidents every month in the US than died on 911, yet comparatively, no one cares about traffic accidents, while going postal and ballistic at 911 (and I'm sure many readers will be offended at even bringing the comparison up). Did we find the authors of 911? Nope. The previous administration quit looking years ago. <br />
<br />
How far were children allowed to roam and play without adult supervision when you were a child? <br />
How far are children allowed to roam without adult supervision today? <br />
<br />
If you're like most people I know, the answers to the above 2 questions are something like &quot;as far I could go, as long as I was home by dinner time&quot; and &quot;they aren't allowed out of the house without supervision.&quot;</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		

		

		

